{"/service/ndnp/ct/batch_ct_aetna_ver02/data/sn92060454/00393346759/1945092901/0164.xml":{"full_text":"X S Wf)t Union dmes X 'S*\n_^omPq'9n- Official Weekly Labor Organ Voicing The Interests Of The American Federation of Labor Campaign!\nVOL. 5, No. 23\nEntered u Second Claaa Matter May 5, 1941, at the Poet Office\nat New Haven, Conn., nnder the Act of March 3, 1879.\nNEW HAVEN, CONN., SATURDAY, SEPTEMBER 29, 1945\nA.F.L. NEWS SERVICE PRICE 5 CENTS\nCtLabor Dept Fights Pro-Labor Ruling\nFEIIMARK SEES PUNNED DRIVE ON IJNONS\n_ \u2014______\nFederation Head\nSays Strikes Are\nBeing Provoked\nUrges Labor To Begin Han\nning For Forthcoming\nPolitical Activity\nStating that the situation\nboth in Connecticut and in\nWashington \u201cclearly show\nthat there is a concerted drive\non to force down the wage and\nliving standards of organized\nlabor,\u201d Harold V. Feinmark,\nsecretary-treasurer of the Con\nnecticut Federation of Labor\ntoday urged all A.F.L. unions\nin this state to begin planning\nnow for political action in\nthis year\u2019s municipal cam\npaigns, and in the state and\nnational elections to be held\nnext year.\nSTRIKES BEING PROVOKED\n\u201cIt is my considered opinion,\u201d\nFeinmark said, \u201cthat the only way\nto explain the fact that Congress\nhas not yet passed legislation to\nsupplement the present inade\nquate Unemployment Compensa\ntion benefits, is the fear that the\ndecent wage standards that organ\nized labor has been able to estab\nlish, will be continued in the post\nwar period. For the same reason,\ncertain employers are working\novertime to provoke strikes.\nThe opposition to the Murray\nWagner-Dingjell Social Security Bill\nis so intense that hearings have not\nyet been held on this measure, one\nof the most important on the legis\nlative calendar if workers and their\nfamilies are to achieve a reasonable\ndegree of security.\n\u201cCongress also is balking at pass\ning such important legislation as a\n65-cent hourly minimum wage, with\nout which purchasing power cannot\nbe maintained; is turning its back on\na permanent Fair Employment Pras\ntices Act, the implication being that\ndiscrimination because of race, reli\ngion, or color are acceptable demo\ncratic practices, once the war emer\ngency officially is over.\u201d\nTHE OLD RUNAROUND\nOn the Connecticut scene, Fein\nmark said, the hesitancy to call a\nspecial session of the Legislature\nis deplorable.\n\u201cIn Connecticut,\u201d he added, \u201cwe\nare told to wait until Washington\nacts. In Washington, we are told\nwe cannot interfere with skate\u2019s\nrights.\n\u201cWe in organized labor are con\nvinced that there is a concerted drive\non to force down the wage and living\nstandards of organized labor, and we\ndo not intend to sit by and let it hap\npen.\n\u201cWe believe that Congress can\nstill be brought to its senses, and\nmade to act for the good of the en\ntire nation. We believe that the\nthinking people of Connecticut will\noppose a policy of \u2018drifting along,\u2019\nand letting \u2018nature take its course.\u2019\n\u201cIn the meantime, however, it is\nnot too early for organized labor\nin this state to begin planning its\n(Continued on Page Two)\nBldg. Trades Agents\nTo Meet Wednesday\nThe business agents of all building\ntrades unions affiliated with the Con\nnecticut State Building Construc\ntion Trades Council will meet at the\nNew Haven Labor Temple on Wed\nnesday, Oct. 3 at 11 A.M. to con\nsider a number of important problems\nconfronting the building trades.\nBuilding trades standards on all\nhighway construction; the situation\nwhich has arisen under Order No. 41,\nand the organizing campaign of the\nstate building trades are among the\nmatters to come before the meeting,\naccording to President Michael J.\nBarry and Secretary-Treasurer James\nO\u2019Kane. This meeting will take the\nplace of the quarterly session of the\nexecutive board of the Council, which\nhas decided to call the business agents\ntogether every three months.\nCollins Charges\nNon-Cooperation\nFederation President Says Conn. Workers Resent Con\ntempt Being Shown By Industry Toward The\nProposals Made By Labor\n___^\nAs We See It\nby\nTHE STAFF\nWE LIKE the remark made by\nBob Schecter, B.A., of New Haven\nMusicians Union. Speaking against\nnon-union bands playing at block\nparties, Bob pointed out that the\ncost of a union band is not larger,\nbecause \u201cfive union musicians can\ndo a better job than 11 or 12 nom j\nunion musicians/\u2019 It\u2019s the truth,\nand applies in other fields *as well.\n\nTOP PRIZE for ingenuity to\ncounteract wartime shortages goes\nto the Waterbury American and Re\npublican, which carried this classi\nfied ad: \u201cOver 60 pieces of inlaid\nlinoleum at 1/3 off. Suitable for\nbathroom, panties and small kitch\nens.\u201d\n\nWHEREVER you find low wage\nlevels, you find working people un\ndernourished, and you find lower\nhealth standards, too; more crime\nand juvenile delinquency, poverty\nand crime walk hand in hand,\ntreading in the footsteps of ignor\nance. It was only a few weeks ago\nthat the surgeon general of the\nUnited States Public Health Serv\nice, testifying before a Senate com\nmittee, pointed out what health\nconditions depend on wage levels.\nWhen working people organize\ninto unions and improve their own\ncondition economically, the inevit\nable result is better health and a\nmore law-abiding people.\nREMEMBER: Sen. Hart of\nConn, joined with such \u201cfriends\u201d\nof the working people of this coun\ntry as Senators Taft, O\u2019Daniel,\nBilbo, and Capehart, to vote against\nthe Berkeley amendment to the\nunemployment compensation bill\ngiving $25 a week as a maximum\nto jobless Americans. Sen. Mc\nMahon voted right!\nOn the roll call, 19 Democrats,\nmostly from the polltax south,\njoined with 32 Republicans to de\nfeat the Barkeley amendment.\nOnly three Republicans, and the\nlone Progressive, LaFollette, voted\nfor the $25 measure.\n\nUNUSUAL reconversion picture\nwas in the Battle Creek (Mich.)\nEnquirer and News:\n3,900 LOSE JOBS\nIN LOCAL PANTS\n\nGEN. MacArthur\u2019s announce\nment that he expected to cut occu\npation troops in Japan down to\nabout 200,000 was a great sur\n(Continued on Page Four)\nRepresents Labor\nVincent j. McGovern,\nPresident of the N. H. Central\nLabor Council, who has been\nappointed Associate Chairman of\nthe newly-created Labor Ad\nvisory Committee of the Com\nmunity Chest and National War\nFund Campaign. (See story on\nthis page.)\nCharging manufacturers organi\nzations in the state with giving only\nlip service to labor-management co\noperation, and declaring that their\npolicies, which he termed \u201creac\ntionary,\u201d are creating bitter resent\nment among organized workers in\nConnecticut, Timothy M. Collins,\npresident of the State Federation of\nLabor, expressed the view in a\nstatement today that the pace of\nreconversion, as a result, would not\nbe as rapid as had been antici\npated and that strife on the indus\ntrial field coupled with considerable\nunemployment was being made in\nevitable.\nNO MUTUALITY\n\u201cIt was the hope of organized\nlabor,\u201d said Collins, \u201cwhen the fall of\nJapan occurred that industry would\nshow a willingness to confer with\nlabor in respect to reconversion prob\nlems in a spirit of mutuality. Two\nevents at least in the past few weeks\nhave indicated that this expectation\nfailed to take into account that reac\ntionary forces continue to dominate\nthe councils of industrial groups in\nConnecticut.\n\u201cFirst, was the slap in the face\ngiven to labor when a committee\nrepresenting manufacturers and\nbusiness men in Fairfield County\nnotified Leroy D. Downs, Area\nWar Manpower Director, that it\nwould not participate in the plan\nned country-wide conference of in\ndustry, labor, agriculture and mu\nnicipal government to study recon\nversion problems and to make\nplans to meet them, upon the spec\nious grounds that it was looking to\nthe conferences in Hartford be\ntween management and labor to set\nthe pattern. These meetings on a\nstate level, of course, are on a\nmuch more restricted basis than\nthose contemplated for Fairfield\nCounty.\nNORWALK, STAMFORD\nPreviously the Norwalk and Stam\nford Manufacturers Councils had re\njected Mr. Downs\u2019 invitation, while\nother city Manufacturers Councils and\nChambers of Commerce had displayed\ninterest. Apparently the economic iso\nlationists prevailed upon the latter to\nwithhold cooperation. Fortunately,\nhowever, in addition to labor the\nmunicipal officers and farm leaders\ngroups have been meeting and have\nbeen hard at work developing pro\ngrams in preparation for the joint\ncounty conference.\nSHAMEFUL PERFORMANCE\n\u201cSecond, was the shameful per\nformance of the legislative agent\nof the State Manufacturers Associa\ntion before the Legislative Council\nin opposing a special session of the\nGeneral Assembly to consider\nmeasures to extend unemployment\nbenefits, to establish a minimum\nwage in the state of 65 cents an\nhour, to undertake an expanded\npublic works program and to\ncreate a state FEPC, despite the\nunited urging of organized labor\nfrom various sections of the state\n(Continued on Page Two)\nEverybody Will\nSign This Petition!\nA plan to get 10,000 New Haven\nresidents to sign petitions endorsing\npay raises, vacations and uniform\nsick leaves for City workers was\nadopted at a meeting of the Joint\nCouncil of Municipal Employes this\nweek at the Hotel Taft. The campaign\nwill be started immediately, members\nof the Council declared.\nThe Council also voted to ask\nMayor John W. Murphy for an im\nmediate conference on these issues and\nwill also seek meetings with the vari\nous commissions and departments in\nvolved.\nEllis Ranen, international represen\ntative of the American Federation of\nState, County and Municipal Em\nployes, A.F.L., presided.\nPresent at the session were: Miss\nAgnes Wallace, Teachers\u2019 League;\nWilliam F. Hartigan, Local 825 of\nAmerican Fire Fighters; Everett W.\nShaw, Police Local 530; John R. Gill,\nsecretary of the Police Local; James\nG. Dooley, vice-president of the Cen\ntral Labor Union of Hartford, and\npresident of Joint Municipal Council\nof Hartford; Harold Spang, Custo\ndians\u2019 Local 278, and Salvatore Adi\nnolfi, treasurer of Police Local 530.\nIF, UNCLE SAM CAN\u2014\n_hi_' V I\nKnock out Hitler with his powerful right\u2014\ni\u2014\u2014-rr-\\-\u2014?*-^\nPut the Jap out with his atomic left hook\u2014\nI I\nHe surely can \u201cfinish\u201d unemployment with both!\nPainters Seek\nEnforcement Of\n1945 Contract\nNew Haven Local Stops\nWork In 3 Shops\u2014New\nYork Wins Victory\nA strong drive to obtain enforce\nment of the contract signed last\nMarch with Local No. 186, Paint\ners Union, by the master painters\nof New Haven who use union la\nbor, is being conducted by the Lo\ncal. All but three shops are abid\ning by the contract, and the union\nmembers of these three shops\nhave refused to report for work\nuntil the terms of the contract are\nobserved. According to Business\nAgent Saul Kreas. the union ex\npects that the situation in these\nthree shops will soon be brought to\na satisfactory conclusion for all\nconcerned.\nUnder the terms of the contract,\nsigned five months ago, members of\nthe union obtained an increase of $1\na day, and vacations with pay.\nEven the three shops which\nhave yet to live up to the terms of\nthe contract had agreed to do so\nlast week, when they were per\nsuaded to reverse their stand by\nJohn J. Fitzgerald of Danbury,\nrepresenting the Conn. Council of\nPainting and Decorating Contrac\ntors, who is known as a non-union\ncontractor.\nFollowing this development, a spec\nial meeting of the membership of\n(Continued on Page Three)\nBausola Succeeded\nBy Christensen\nFrank Bausola, until recently finan\ncial secretary of the Hartford Cen\ntral Labor Union and secretary-treas\nurer of Teamsters and Chauffeurs\u2019\nLocal 559, tendered his resignation at\nthe last Central Body meeting, effec\ntive immediately.\nMr. Bausola is now a resident of\nNorwich, where he has entered busi\nness as a partner in a restaurant. He\nhad previously resigned as secretary\ntreasurer of Local 559, and his suc\ncessor is Andrew Christensen, who\nwas formerly business agent and trus\ntee.\nAll Labor Rallies\nTo Support Of\nChest War Fund\nA.F.L. Urges Membership\nTo Give \u201cUtmost Of\nOur Generosity\u201d\nOrganized labor throughout Con\nnecticut is organizing to help the\nCommunity Chest and National\nWar Fund campaigns in the vari\nous cities and towns of the state\ngo over the top. All central labor\nbodies, and city and state leaders\nhave unanimously endorsed the\ncampaign, which, according to\nA.F.L. President William Green,\ndemands \u201cthe utmost of our gen\nerosity, thus making it possible for\nthe National War Fund\u2019s agencies\nto function at full capacity.\u201d\nIn each city and town, funds are\nbeing raised for important local agen\ncies, and for the National War Fund,\nwhich supports the USO, United Sea\nmen\u2019s Service, and 15 overseas relief\nagencies aiding the hungry and un\nfortunate people plundered by the\nNazis and the Japanese.\nADVISORY COMMITTEE\nIn New Haven, labor\u2019s partici\npation in the drive has been step\nped up by the formation of an\n(Continued on Page Three)\nSenate Group For\nPoll Tax Measure\nWASHINGTON (FP) The\nHatch subcommittee of the Senate\njudiciary committee has formally re\nported HR 7, the polltax repeal bill,\nto the full committee by a vote of 3\nto 2.\nSen. Carl Hatch (D\u201e N. M.) an\nnounced the subcommittee action,\nwhich was greeted by Mrs. Katherine\nShryver, executive secretary of the\nNational Committee to Abolish the\nPolltax, as \u201cwonderful progress.\u201d\nSen. Pat McCarran (D., Nev.)\nchairman of the judiciary committee,\nhas promised prompt action on HR 7,\nand Mrs. Shryver said \u201cwe are con\nfident that his promise will be ful\nfilled, and we are equally confident\nthat the Senate will adopt cloture, if\nnecessary, to insure the rights of the\nmajority to vote for a bill and decid<\nthe issue on its merits.\u201d\nState Plan For\nBuilding Trades\nAnd Contractors\nCarpenters* And Masons*\nApprentice Training Pro\ngram Open To All\nPrentice White, Administrator\nof the Connecticut State Housing\nAuthority has announced a state\nwide program to fill the need for\nbuilding mechanics and to pre\npare for the coming building boom,\nthrough an apprentice training\nplan for carpenters and masons.\nWUh a definite need for trained\nartisans in the construction field, Mr.\nWhite said he obtained the coopera\ntion of the Connecticut Building\nTrades and Construction Council, the\nState Apprenticeship Council and\nrepresentatives of the Apprenticeship\nTraining Service (War Manpower\nCommission) in setting up recom\nmended apprenticeship standards for\nthe carpentry and masonry trades.\nThese standards have been approved\nby joint state committees represent\ning general contractors and labor, the\npersonnel of which is as follows:\nLabor:\nMichael J. Barry, Hartford\nG. Joslyn, New Haven\nJ. O\u2019Kane, Bridgeport\nG. Sabo, Waterbury\nCarmen DiCorcia, Hartford\nGeneral Contractors:\nM. Allyn Wadhams, Hartford\nCharles S. Phelps, Meriden\nPaul Hawley, Torrington\nEdwin Moss, Bridgeport\nJ. A. St. Germain, New London\nDesiring to make immediately avail\nable for returriing servicemen and\nothers the opportunity to learn a\ntrade; a bulletin, copies of the stand\nards, application blanks to the unions,\nas well as a letter of transmittal out\nlining the need for men in this field\nand the procedure to be followed are\nbeing forwarded throughout the State\nto the 18 United States Employment\nService offices, 65 draft boards and\n146 local Reemployment and Veter\nans\u2019 Advisory Committees.\nBenefits to veterans under rub\nlie Law No. 16, \u201cAn Act Providing\nfor Vocational Rehabilitation of\nDisabled Veterans\u201d, and Public\nAct No. 346, \u201cServicemen\u2019s Read\njustment Act of 1944\u201d (commonly\ncalled the GI Bill of Rights) are\navailable to those who undertake\nthe apprenticeship training in ad\ndition to the remuneration as out\nlined in the standards.\nThe complete cooperation of Wil\nliam J. Fitzgerald, Manpower Direc\ntor in charge of the Connecticut\noffices of the United States Employ\nment Service, Commander John F.\nRobinson, State Director of the Se\nlective Service System, and J. Everfett\nLight, Director of the Connecticut\nVeterans Reemployment and Advisory\nCommission, was procured and com\nmunications were forwarded to their\nrespective agencies, requesting assist\n(Continued on Page Two)\nWe\u2019re On KKK Blacklist\nWICHITA, Kans. (FP) Last\nmeeting of the Ku Klux Klan here\npassed a resolution demanding that all\nKICK employers \u2018refuse to hire any\none who possesses a union card.\u201d\nThe KKK in Wichita now has a\nmembership of 875, the last 475 of\nwhom paid $50 apiece initiation fees.\nUpholds Labor\nWilliam H. Connelly, unem\nployment Compensation Com\nmissioner, whose pro-labor rul\ning is being appealed by the\nState Labor Department. (See\nstory on Page 1.)\nw ^_\nConnelly Decision\nIrks U. C. Division\nCommissioner Rules Paid Vacations Have No Affect On\nUnemployment Benefits, So Labor Dept. Rushes\nTo Superior Court\u2014Labor Startled By\nDivision\u2019s Reactionary Rulings\nOrganized labor in this state, which in recent months has\nbeen startled by the reactionary policies of the Unemploy\nment Compensation Division of the Connecticut Department\nol Labor, this week had additional cause to wonder.\nThe newest bomb-shell thrown into the ranks of workers\nby the Labor Department is the fact that it has given notice\nthat it will appeal to the Superior Court to obtain reversal\nof a decision which holds that vacation fund benefits are in\nno way related to unemployment compensation.\nTHE PLAIN FACTS\nHere are the facts:\nIn a case involving the International Ladies Garment\nWorkers Union, AFL, which has more than 6,000 members\nin this state, the. State Labor Department ruled that if a\nworker loses his job, but has a week\u2019s paid vacation coming\nto him, unemployment benefits will start a week later than\nusual.\nPreviously the I.L.G.W.U. had challenged this interpreta\ntion in hearings held before Assistant Attorney General\n\u201cA Strange Situation Indeed!\u201d\nJacob L. Banach, Connecticut manager of the I.L.G.W.U., to\nday told The Union Times that he had instructed all members of his\norganization to ask for a hearing when their unemployment bene\nfits are reduced by the Labor Department because of the vacation\nfund. This will be done nntil the Superior Court rules on the Labor\nDepartment\u2019s appeal.\n\u201cNaturally we are surprised at the Labor Department\u2019s appeal,\u201d\nMr. Banach said. \u201cThe Labor Department was established to help\nthe workingman, and normally, we would expect that it would abide\nby Commissioner Connelly\u2019s ruling. It is indeed a strange situation\nwhen the Commissioner goes to the Superior Court to obtain a re\nversal of a pro-labor ruling.\u201d\nHarry Silver8tone. In the meantime, however, Organizer Lou\nOrons appealed the ruling on behalf of five employees of the\nJoniel Sportswear Co., of South Norwalk. The appeal was\nheard by Compensation Commissioner William H. Connelly,\nwho reversed the decision of the Unemployment Compensa\ntion Director, and ordered that full unemployment benefits\nbe paid. The Connecticut Labor Department, of which the\nUnemployment Compensation Division is a part, has now an\nnounced notice of its intention to appeal Commissioner Con\nnelly\u2019s pro-labor ruling to the Superior Court.\nSECOND REVERSAL OF DIVISION\nThis is the second time in recent weeks that Unemploy\nment Compensation Commissioners have reversed anti-labor\nrulings of the state\u2019s U. C. division.\nThis case is of great importance to organized labor, be\ncause a great majority of collective bargaining agreements\ncontain provisions which provide for paid vacations. The\nI.L.G.W.U. charges that Connecticut is the only state in the\nunion where it has contracts, that vacation funds are con\nsidered part of unemployment benefits.\nIn hearings before Assistant Attorney General Silverstone\nthis summer, the I.L.G.W.U. challenged the Labor Depart\nment\u2019s contention that workers are ineligible for unemploy\nment insurance when they have received vacation fund bene\nfits. They presented data showing that the vacation benefit\nfunds cannot be viewed as payment coming from the em\nployer inasmuch as the latter relinquishes all title to such\nfunds.\nNO CONNECTION EXISTS'\nThe I.L.G.W.U. likewise presented proof that no connec\ntion exists between vacation payments and compensation for\nloss of wages by emphasizing the fact that the benefit is paid,\nin many cases, to members who have not lost wages through\nlay-offs or slack periods.\nThe South Norwalk ruling came while the union was\nawaiting a decision by Assistant Attorney General Silverstein\non appeals presented in behalf of workers throughout the\nstate.\nOrganizer Orons, who successfully argued the case for the\nunion in that city, and Sam Janis of the Bridgeport local,\nwill work with Goodman Block of the I.L.G.W.U. Research\nDept, in preparing to meet the state\u2019s appeal against Com\nmissioner Connelly\u2019s decision.\nWILL GO TO SUPREME COURT\nIt is announced that the union is determined to carry the\ncase to the Supreme Court of the state in order to protect the\nworkers\u2019 rights to both vacation benefits and unemployment\ninsurance compensation. I\nU.C. Claims In Conn.\nContinue To Mount\n_\nIn the past week 65,768 out-of-work\nindividuals filed unemployment bene\nfit claims in Connecticut. This is an\nincrease of 8.1 per cent from the pre\nvious week.\nInitial claims filed dropped 30.2 per\ncent to 6,087 while continued claims\nincreased 14.7 per cent over the pre\nceding week to 55,336. The Employ\nment Security Division mailed out\n19,342 civilian checks and 2,078 vet\neran\u2019s checks for the week, a total of\n$393,976, an increase of 184.7 per cent.\nThe average check paid to unemployed\nworkers was $20.37 and closed claims\ntotalled 1,634.\nHartford continued to lead the\nState with 14,115, but this was a 7.8\nper cent decrease from last week.\nBridgeport was second highest with\n9,957, up 22.3 per cent and New\nHaven third with 8,270, up 14.1 per\ncent.","height":"26523","width":"20721"}}
